<paper id="1521395498"><title>Advanced Replica Management with Reptor</title><year>2003</year><authors><author org="European Organization For Nuclear Research" id="2984079129">Peter Z. Kunszt</author><author org="European Organization For Nuclear Research" id="1965942009">Erwin Laure</author><author org="European Organization For Nuclear Research" id="2095364609">Heinz Stockinger</author><author org="European Organization For Nuclear Research" id="2463969832">Kurt Stockinger</author></authors><n_citation>39</n_citation><doc_type>Conference</doc_type><references><reference>1496966732</reference><reference>1970019308</reference><reference>2096122599</reference><reference>2096940531</reference><reference>2127556182</reference><reference>2164998175</reference></references><venue id="1155899826" type="C">International Conference on Parallel Processing</venue><doi>10.1007/978-3-540-24669-5_110</doi><keywords><keyword weight="0.5823">Replication (computing)</keyword><keyword weight="0.44349">Computer science</keyword><keyword weight="0.45148">Petabyte</keyword><keyword weight="0.61716">Data grid</keyword><keyword weight="0.49999">Usability</keyword><keyword weight="0.51781">Fault tolerance</keyword><keyword weight="0.0">Replica management</keyword><keyword weight="0.50058">Grid</keyword><keyword weight="0.51144">Storage Resource Broker</keyword><keyword weight="0.46044">Distributed computing</keyword></keywords><publisher>Springer, Berlin, Heidelberg</publisher><abstract>Data replication is one of the best known strategies to achieve high levels of availability and fault tolerance, as well as minimal access times for large, distributed user communities using a world-wide Data Grid. In certain scientific application domains the data volume can reach the order of several petabytes; in these domains data replication and access optimization play an important role in the manageability and usability of the Grid.</abstract></paper>